Sourdough bakery, mill, shop & school in Hackney.

social_posts.post_text:
📚It’s justttt about two years since we released our first book ‘Hackney Wild’ and for the whole of December we’ll be putting our pride and joy on a special offer for £15! Get your copy in either our Hackney or Poplar bakehouse and start baking!

This anthology of e5 over the past decade is filled with great photos and illustrations, with a compendium of sourdough and our other favourite cake and lunch recipes, allll of which have been contributed by our wonderful staff over the years! Whats not to love?   Feeling emosh, enjoy! -From your e5 elves just like this one👆🏼!

It’s only the 1st of December and we’re back with the favourite of the season… Mince Pies! 🎄  This year we are delighted to tell you that our mince pie pastry is 100% e5 stoneground flour from our mill (🥳!) and delicious @fenfarmdairy butter. What’s inside? An aged ‘mincemeat’ filling that helps the flavours meld and deepen with house-made candied peel and nuts from @foodandforest ! Topped with a demeamera crust this lil pie is quite boozy, not too sweet and has delicately flakey pastry. 

Mmmmm… find these on the pastry counter daily until that big person comes! 🎅🏽🧑🏿‍🎄🤶🏻

Here’s a couple of our all time classics! 

Our Hackney Wild is made from stoneground flour, using a blend from our favourite mills this loaf is mostly made up of flour fresh from our in-house mill! 

Our Multigrain contains a variety of wholemeal flours with sprouted wheat grains mixed into the dough to give it some sweetness and texture topped off with a blend of mixed seeds! 

Which loaf are you loving? 😘🌾

Our Stollen is here! 💫

Stollen is a classic German enriched dough, traditionally made to be enjoyed over Christmas. Our Stollen is naturally leavened (100% sourdough), without any commercial yeast. It has generous amounts of dried fruits, almonds and house-made candied peel that had previously been soaking in brandy and citrus juice. The centre features a rich and soft marzipan with the best @foodandforest almonds. That’s not all, as it’s still hot out of the oven, they are soaked in melted butter and rolled in icing sugar!

Make start to finish with love from your e5 elves and available at both Hackney & Poplar sites🎄

We’ve been making Speculaas biscuits filled for those Christmassy feels all December and we also now have our annual giant Speculaas people being wrapped up to go to good homes!
 Our filled Speculaas are made using @fenfarmdairy butter with a marzipan filling made from @foodandforest almonds, house-made candied peel and warming spice mix.

The Speculaas people have the same delicious spiced biscuit but are made using traditional wooden moulds and also have a healthy dosage of flour from our mill. 

What do they taste like? Katie says “they basically taste like Christmas!” So, if this doesn’t make Christmas feel a bit more special, I don’t know what will… 🌟

Please note that our Millhouse will be having a makeover! 

So, while a new floor settles in we will be back open tomorrow but serving you from our ‘original’ cafe space! A little time machine back to sipping coffees and buying bread from in-front of our bakers oven. Ahhhh 😌

We’ll be open from 7:30am until 4pm and we’ll have you back in our spacious millhouse from Friday 30th! 

Hope you’ve been stuffed with lots of treats but are ready for your e5 favourites☕️

Thaaaaats a wrap!!! 

As we’ve reached the end of the year we would love to say a big thank you to all our customers and staff that make us sooo mwah! 💖

It’s been real, so enjoy some fun piccys of only a snippet of who make up e5 🥰

Have an amazing New Year and here’s to 2023! 🎆

👑 Happy New Year everyone! We hope you’ve had a good one and to see the New Year of 2023 in right we’re busy prepping our Galette des Rois! 👑

This seasonal favourite is made using @fenfarmdairy butter and our e5 stonemilled flour, Millers Choice! Inside the layers of delicious flaky puff pastry is a filling of toasted almond frangipane with nuts from @foodandforest mixed with creme patisserie using @ivyhousefarmdairy !

Our féve will be a hidden whole almond inside, if you’re lucky enough to find it, you’ll be king for the day! 🤞🏼

Pre-order your nutty, buttery Galette des Rois through our office or shop from TOMORROW! We’re offering a standard size, pictured, that is 6-8 slices or a larger size of 10-12! Please note we will have very limited slices available from our pastry counter so don’t sleep on it! 🥲

🧑🏽‍💻info@e5bakehouse.com ☎️020 8525 2890

🥕 It’s only our Carrot Chill and Feta Puff, the beloved Spanakopita’s friendly rival! 🌶  A warming savoury treat with delicious feta style cheese mixed with a carrot curry spice mix. Our carrots are first roasted in the oven to give more aroma and flavour, followed by blitzing, mixing with fresh herbs and then wrapped in our favourite puff pastry that uses the best @fenfarmdairy butter. 

I’m here for the season’s change of our triangular shaped pastry, are you? 🧡

What’s King Cookie? 👑🍪  Well, we’re feeling pretty lucky to have collaborated with such amazing, and local, breweries like @howlinghops and @claptoncraft who have made a delicious stout recipe based on our most popular cookie, the chocolate rye! 

This brew features very special cocoa nibs that were delivered to us by Sail Cargo which then were roasted in house by our very own chocolatier and baker Paulo! To add that little extra luxury, the e5 pastry team whipped up the vanilla extract for this indulgent beverage.   Sweet chocolatey, bitter espresso, rich goodness with just a hint of rye malt to balance the flavours. Now being sold at e5 and with our friends at Howling Hops and Clapton Craft -grab a can, a glass, maybe even a cookie… and let us know what you think! 🍻  P.s. Choccy Rye’s back on the counter next week!

For the routine weekend brunch lovers, this one is for you! 

We’re settling into 2023 and it’s back to our weekend brunch menu as usual from today, featuring this special treat the Meatball Marinara Focaccia sandwich with parmesan! 

Our other weekend dishes include… • French Toast -try it savoury or sweet! • Scrambled Eggs on Toast • Mushroom & Leeks on Toast • Butter Beans on Toast • Bacon & Egg Sandwich • Granola & Yoghurt • Seasonal Porridge • Halloumi Bun • Salmon on Rye

See you soon hungry people! Menu until 3pm Sat & Sun 🍳

Whaaaaat, it’s been one whole year that we started ‘Eco-January’ that snowballed into seeing us through the rest of 2022, and beyond! 🥳

Of course, we couldn’t have done this without you and are so happy you’ve stuck by us drinking in, bringing your own cups, purchasing @huskee cups or using @reuser.club ! 

With the ever-growing concern surrounding waste we hope to keep trying our best to make an impact by eliminating our single-use cups. We know it hasn’t always been easy, but we are really proud to have made this decision work for us, and hopefully you too! 💚

Whether you’re a quick sipper or steady Eddie, we’re always happy to offer mugs and accept your wildest keep cups. Lastly, it’s amazing to be a part of the expanding @reuser.club community with so many other local cafe’s in our area, so we hope that makes things a little sweeter for those on the go! 

Lots of love and here’s to another year! 
☕♻️☕♻️

We're proud to be a collection point for Growing Communities scheme! 🌽🥦🍅

Growing Communities veg bag scheme brings you fresh, organic, seasonal fruit and veg every week whilst bringing about real, positive change for people and planet. So, whether its a New Years resolution of yours, or cooking seasonally is something you fancy trying, we’re happy to share their January welcome offer with you! 

If you’d like to join, sign up before 31/01/23 and you can claim a free bag of delicious organic veggies in your first month. If you’re in the first 100 people to sign up you will also receive a free veg scrubbing brush! Select FOLLOWTHECARROT as the joining reason at the checkout to get these little treats from the team at Growing Communities.

🥕👨🏻‍🌾🥕🧑🏾‍🌾🥕

Our December’s delivery of @honest_toil is pretty special! 🫒

This oil is the first of the seasons extra virgin olive oil, hand-picked from olives that were growing on trees just two weeks before they were boxed and packed to us! 

The result is this ridiculously fresh, raw and green tasting extra virgin olive oil, with a peppery spice, and flavours of fresh cut grass. Cold-pressed within hours at the local press in rural Greece, the oil is unblended and unfiltered with a fantastically low acidity. 

We’re really proud that this oil finds its way into pretty much every department at the bakery -we love using it mostly in our cakes, doughs and kitchen recipes! It would be soo rude to boast about this oil and not sell it too… we have 3L boxes available in our shop of this new harvest. 

Enjoy these lovely pics from Honest Toil 💚

🇰🇭 Love Drunk Cambodian ♥️  It’s our first supper club of the year and who better to do it with than our friends from Mamapen! Five courses you’ll be head over heels for from chefs Kaneda Pen and Jo Garner (our beloved past e5 pastry whizz!)

It’s a celebration of Cambodian beer food and a loving nod to Jo's Scottish heritage -swipe for the full menu! Full vegetarian menu also available 🥬

Tickets are £50 per person and can be found on @mamapenldn or in our bio!
Doors 6:30pm 🖤 Food 7:30pm

🍊Just landed at e5 is our annual batch of Sicilian blood and naval oranges, mandarins and grapefruits!🍊 

For those of you needing a little extra zest (and colour!) in these chilly months we’ll be keeping our shops stocked of these beauties that REALLY are delicious! Marmalade production is also in full swing so keep your eyes peeled for jars of this citrus over the next few weeks… which will obvs go perfect with your e5 loaf 😌  🏔 Lots of love to @laudani_sicilia_inside , their fruits are lovingly grown at the foot of Mount Etna and employ 100% natural cultivation and conservation techniques without the use of chemical additives or waxes! 

Tanti baci! 😘

👨🏻‍🍳 We’re hiring pastry chefs! 👩🏾‍🍳

We have two great positions available for experienced pastry chefs, one at our Hackney site, the other at Poplar! Both sites provide the opportunity to work with our amazing suppliers UK ingredients and seasonal produce and alongside a wonderfullll team of e5 bakers, millers, chefs, roasters & baristas! 💖

Both positions:  🥐Lamination experience preferential  🥐Part-time role that can develop into full-time 🥐Start ASAP  To apply please email your CV to jobs@e5bakehouse.com with ‘Pastry Chef’ in the subject line -speak soon!

Its been a hot second since we’ve shown you our seasonal galette sooo… here it is! Forced rhubarb and vanilla custard!

Our rhubarb is macerated in vanilla sugar and milk from @ivyhousefarmdairy makes up our creamy vanilla custard. House-made kefir also goes into our classic sweet galette dough alongside the one and only @fenfarmdairy butter and Cann Mills light and dark spelt flour. Finished with a crunchy demerara crust. Mmm-hmm. 

💗 Cute fact -our forced rhubarb is from 5 generations of Yorkshire rhubarb growers and are regarded the leaders in their field! E Oldroyd & Sons 💗

On the counter for the rest of the month!

The Alpujarras Retreat is back! 🌞

🇪🇸 29th April - 6th of May 🇪🇸  This is a week long retreat where you’ll cover making a variety of different types of breads using techniques we use here at the bakery! In true e5 style, you’ll also have the opportunity to be baking with some locally milled Spanish stoneground heritage flour from different local mills, one being @rincondelsegura ! Come as a beginner or as someone with experience, it’s perfect for those wanting to gain more knowledge behind sourdough baking for different types of bread 🤓  You’ll be staying in the beautiful converted village houses that is @laschimeneas and will have the opportunity to make the most of this setting as your baking schedule will be largely dictated by the weather. For sunny days you can be free to ramble outdoors guided by your hosts Emma & David.   Find more information from what’s included to the breads you’ll be baking on our website using the link in our bio! 

Book by emailing info@laschimeneas.com 

📸 Pics by @envie_lavie

We’ll be serving all sorts of pancakes, galettes, crêpes from 9am - 3pm alongside our daily breakfast and lunch options. 

Menu will be released soon in our stories so keep an eye out! For now you can already dream about those crispy buckwheat galettes 💚 We sure have missed them on our menu! What’s your favourite type of pancake?

Feeling extra motivated after welcoming the team from @e5bakehouse and @e5poplarbakehouse for a visit to discuss social enterprise within baking. We spent the afternoon chatting about our work employing people in prison, and e5's Just Bread programme, which supports refugees through training and employment.

We're excited to continue the conversation around baking with purpose and using this amazing, collaborative industry to fight for social justice.

We're also stoked for head baker Paul to try out this beautiful flour, freshly milled in house at e5's Hackney bakery on their Astrié stone mill! 🌾🥖

‼️ New ‼️ 

The Seeded Stockholm comes as a replacement for our old friend, the Multigrain. We wanted to still give you the joys of having a seeded loaf but now using more of our very own stoneground flour in the dough! This loaf is chock full of more locally sourced seeds and grains. They’re slowly toasted and soaked overnight  which makes for a very digestible and nutritious loaf. 

The Seeded Stockholm has a very high highdration which makes it moist and lasts for ages. With it’s 1kg size it can feed your whole household for days, if you can keep it for that long...

Easy to freeze too, just pop it into your toaster direct from the freezer and enjoy with your morning cuppa! ☕️

This last month we’ve been making good use of all the seasonal fruits in their abundance. We’ve been admiring the beautiful and juicy blood oranges 🍊 Sicilian lemons 🍋 and the floral goodness of Bergamots, alongside the brightest of pinks that comes with the forced rhubarb and it’s perfect level of tartness.

You can now find all our marmalades and jams on our shelves. The kitchen has also been making beautiful salads and pickles as well as compotes and roasted rhubarb to go on our vegan porridge and granola.💘 

What have you been making with yours? Comments👇

We’re having a fundraiser at the bakehouse in Hackney for the people of Syria and Turkey. The earthquakes have brought enormous devastation to these areas and solidarity is much needed. We’re trusting in our community to come through. ❤️ 

All profits will go to @ahbap , a trustworthy organisation that provides all kinds of help locally in Turkey and to @thehandsupfoundation who we've collaborated gmany times with in the past for our Syrian Supper Clubs. 

We're collaborating with the great people of @pacificsocialclub who'll be bringing lots of their precious vinyl and will carry us through from the afternoon into the evening. 

We’ll be providing an amazing menu cooked entirely by volunteers from the bakehouse and beyond and it will be priced using the Pay What You Feel payment structure. This means there will be a suggested price but any amount you can donate is appreciated, as little or as much as you like!

We'll be opening up our bar where you can purchase a selection of our delicious drinks.

Please bring your friends, family, neighbours and donate generously!

Thank you to our amazing team of volunteers and sponsors for their generosity. 

With love,
E5 Bakehouse

Photograph by @kaan_diskaya

Thank you to all our wonderful volunteers, DJs, sponsors and of course all the people that donated funds going towards the @thehandsupfoundation and @ahbap ! We had a heartwarming and wholesome evening surrounded by the best people with the best tunes and nourished by a great team of cooks. 

The pide game was strong! Sucuk was unknown to many but combined with that stringy mozzarella made for what was low-key the star of the pide show. The köfte were just smoky enough from the first bbq of the year. Thank you to those who dedicated hours to slicing and frying so many onions for mixing through the bulgur and lentil mujadara--you know who you are. The aubergines were finished with a light sprinkle of earthy Syrian za’atar imported in dubious looking packages from a trip to Lebanon by some of our staff. The baklava and sekerpare were soaked overnight in a gorgeously thick syrup with a hint of orange blossom water for a sweet and sticky finish accompanied by some Palestinian dates and dried apricots.

We are very grateful to be reminded of what is possible to achieve through solidarity in such a short timespan. 

If you were not able to contribute on the night and still wish to, please visit the websites of both The Hands Up Foundation and AHBAP and consider donating still.

Thank you, thank you, thank you.

We've invited Sarah and Aitana from The Little Cooking Pot who have recently published a beautiful book collecting some of their go to recipes and stories from their many travels. Their cooking offers some fresh insights on cooking with British seasonal food, following an agricultural-based calendar. Their book serves as a guide to growing, eating and preserving seasonally. We're very happy to stock their book in our shop and now even more delighted to work with them for this brilliant meal. 

The Supper Club has been set up with our 'Not Just Bread’ programme in mind. All profits made the will go towards funding this, which is the newest iteration of the 'Just Bread’ programme that e5 Bakehouse has been running with the Refugee Council since around 2012 following the beginning of the Syrian refuggee crisis. This May/June we will run an 8-week long course which teaches 10-12 people with refugee status how to make sourdough. But it doesn’t just stop there!

The course will also teach many other skills associated with working in and running a bakery, from making jams and cookies, to costing, packaging and sales. The participants are always from a broad range of backgrounds e.g. Ethiopia, Iran, Syria, Sudan, Turkey and Georgia to name but a few, and with them they bring a wealth of culinary knowledge and skills which we encourage them to share and celebrate. The course is not only a way to share our passion for making sourdough and skill sharing but to show that it's possible to do this together in an inclusive, warm environment that can build confidence and friendships.

Many of our alumni have gone on to work in bakeries, for example many now work at Poplar Bakehouse and some have gone on to start their own business! So, why did we change the name after so many years? Well we realised that for us, making bread is never just about bread, but making connections, sharing ideas and strengthening communities.

Link for tickets in our bio!

Einkorn! 🌾 

What a beautiful wheat. Einkorn was the first domesticated variety of wheat that we think arrived in Britain over 6000 years ago! We’ve been making our Einkorn tinned loaf for a few years now, but we got a new little friend that has elevated what could be mistaken for, on first sight - an unremarkable loaf. If you haven’t noticed yet, our loaf now has freshly-flaked einkorn on top of the bread for extra flavour and texture. Don’t be mistaken by its humble appearance, our einkorn is full of flavour with gentle nutty and umami notes and a sweet wheat aroma with an unusually light texture, the crumb being similar to that of our rye.

Einkorn is what we call a heritage variety of wheat, they are robust, stand beautifully tall in the field with deep-reaching roots which pick up many essential nutrients and minerals in the soil and I hope you agree, are very tasty in baked goods! 

Heritage grains are environmentally sustainable crops because they tend to be more resilient to the effects of climate change and pests and grow especially well using organic and regenerative farming methods without having to rely on chemical fertilisers, pesticides or herbicides. 

Thank you to all the researchers, farmers, millers and bakers for their longstanding contributions to the changes in sustainable farming, growing, milling and baking. It’s great to see the efforts of all these people and their shared knowledge come together in a simple tinned loaf. 

Top tip: spread generously with butter and a sprinkle of sea salt. ✨

🌈🌱Spring time at Fellows 🌱🌈 

With lambs in the field, new leaves filling the polytunnels, fresh rain filled ponds, young fruit trees in the ground and toads under the mypex - there’s new life at every corner Fellows !

Purple sprouting broccoli, mixed salad leaves, rhubarb  and herbs have been harvested recently, with tomatoes, chillis, beetroot, fennel, celeriac, kale, squash, cucumbers and more on the way. 

We can’t wait to see more flowers ready for cutting and eating now the sun’s out, plus the return of soft fruits 🍓 
 
There’s a lot to look forward to this season, including regular wood fired bread bakes and brand new dates for workshops and events. Details of willow weaving classes with @windeweaves and a very special baking retreat in August are up on our website. More soon !

Some exciting Spring News! 🌞

There are two new classes happening at e5 Bakehouse:

🍋 Flatbread & Mezze Class

You’ll be shown how to mix, shape and bake Turcoman style sourdough flatbreads alongside make a beautiful selection of some of our favourite mezzes such as labneh, beetroot borani, carrot muhammara, hummus,… after baking your breads and preparing the mezze, you’ll settle down for a cosy communal feast enjoying the fruits of your labour with some nice drinks.

🥖Advanced Sourdough Shaping 

This one is for those looking for a deep-dive into shaping sourdough. We’ll be focussing on specific skills and techniques for making a veriety of different breads, from a rustic, free-form loaf, similar to our beloved Stockholm, to Southern French fougasse and the elusive sourdough baguette. During this hlf day course you will discuss how shaping relates to fermentation, flour choice and baking approach.

More details on our classes are on our website via link in bio! 

Come join our bakers and chefs on one of our classes as we’re sure you’ll step away with heaps of new knowledge, a full belly, good chats and possibly new friends. 🌱

We have added new class dates for our Sourdough Bread Class, Pastry Class and Pizza Class!

Hello? Who’s there? 📞 

New cookie alert 

This one is crunchy, chewy and punchy! It has it all 💕 It’s made with rye flour, housemade candied ginger, Original beans Dark Chocolate and a bit of treacle for that perfect slightly savoury after taste. Rolled in some beautifully golden Demerara sugar for a slight crunch. 

It also happens to be vegan, so come by and give it a try! No doubt it will be one of our bestsellers.

Some people think that making bread every day can be repetitive. We surely don’t think so! Working with sourdough means you are working with a product that is alive ❤️‍🔥

Add predominantly freshly stone milled flour, mostly heritage and population wheat varieties into the mix, and really no two days look the same in the life of an e5 baker. 

Butttt… let’s be honest, sometimes it’s nice to experiment and for the bakers to have the chance to show a little flair 💅🏻 This is where the Porridge Bread comes in! Each month, a different baker in our baking team is crowned the ‘porridge monarch’, (pictures of the ceremony only for staff, sorry 👑) and with this title comes the great responsibility of developing a new porridge loaf recipe. 

The base dough remains the same (we take some of our Hackney Wild dough) and then we make a porridge which could be made out of any grain or cereal. Sometimes we toast the grains, or perhaps we sprout them! They can be combined with seeds, nuts or fruit; spices, herbs or other such additions. Honey! Treacle! There are a myriad of possibilities allowing the bakers’ imagination to go wild. 

We develop the gluten structure needed using the base dough, and then we mix the porridge through which means we can be playful with ingredients and flavours without compromising the bread’s ability to rise. You can always expect a loaf that is full of flavour, nutritional value and keeping fresh for days because of all that moisture locked into the crumb…

June’s 'porridge monarch' is Fin and his chosen porridge bread is barley, chia seed and treacle. Delicious.

What’s been your favourite or what porridge loaves do you all bake? 👇

Baking Weaving & mindfulness retreat 25th - 28th of August 

🌼🍕🌱🟡🌾🧘🏾‍♀️🌞🧺

@fellows_farm are delighted to welcome their friend Hui Hui Ng, an experienced Vipassana meditation practitioner and Hatha Yoga teacher to collaborate with us (Ben Mackinnon @mackinnon.benjamin and Femke Lemmens @windeweaves ) on a baking, weaving and mindfulness retreat.

This is a chance to get away from it all for a relaxing, insightful and energising weekend in the countryside. As a small group of 12, we will be baking sourdough bread and pizzas in our wood fired oven, weaving willow baskets with willow grown right here on the farm, eating delicious food grown in our organic market garden, doing yoga and meditating with Hui, developing practices which you can continue beyond the weekend. 

During the weekend, we'll use mindfulness exercises to connect and ground ourselves with each experience. A morning mindful yoga and meditation is offered to start the day, and an evening meditation to close.

Accommodation | Camping included and available in our wildflower meadow. Bring your own tent, or hire a Bell Tent from Norfolk Bell Tent.
Food | All food and drink included (this will be an alcohol free weekend)
Price | £100

More information | Once you’ve booked your place, we’ll be in touch nearer the time to give you some more information about what to bring and what to expect! 

Booking via link in Bio 👆

Ah the Cornish Yarg. A gorgeous pasteurised cheese made from cow’s milk in Truro, West Cornwall. 🐄 

At some point in the 1980s, while digging around in his attic, Cornish farmer Alan Gray stumbled across a 17th century recipe for nettle-wrapped cheese and set about recreating it. Today the cheese is produced by Catherine Mead and her team at Lynher Dairies in Ponsanooth, Cornwall. 

The nettles are foraged from the local hedgerows each spring and frozen so they can be used throughout the year. By the time the nettles are brushed onto the cheese, they have lost their sting, but they still play an important role in forming the attractive rind for which the cheese is known. The animal rennet Cornish Yarg that we sell is made solely from milk from Lynher Dairy's own herd of Ayrshire cows and is matured there for 21 to 28 days before coming to @nealsyarddairy 

The nettle leaves give the rind an earthy taste and inside you find a fine crumbly core. Absolutely perfect for a summer cheese board served with some cucumber pickles, slices of baguette, peppery olive oil and sea salt if you ask us!

BROUDOU is an independent collective which works together with researchers, farmers, artists and other actors within the food landscape in Tunis. Their field research, immersive & embodied workshops, and food experiences, are archived in the form of a yearly printed publication. BROUDOU Magazine is a publication and research platform at the intersection between food, politics and art, dedicated to exploring the future of food in Tunisia. 

Issue 01 of the magazine investigates an anthropology of bread and regroups reflections on the cultural, social, political, ecological, emotional, spiritual, and economic aspects of bread production and consumption.

BROUDOU was founded in 2021 by Aziza Gorgi, Emily Sarsam, and Yasmin Houamed as the manifestation of a deep connection over food shared between friends. Motivated by a growing disconnection with the origins of what we eat in urban environments, the Magazine offers knowledge and inspiration to think about food’s political, cultural and social lives while also inviting readers to engage in practices where food reflects systems that enrich rather than exploit their source materials. 

BROUDOU's latest issue is dedicated to olive oil and was launched in June 2023. 

BROUDOU Magazine is currently supported by @goetheinstitut_tunis 

Both publications will be available for sale in our Millhouse shop!

Are you a sourdough whizz looking to hone your skills? Well, look no further than our newly developed ‘Advanced Sourdough Shaping Masterclass’. A jam-packed afternoon full of dough chat and the science behind the techniques. All of our teachers are highly-skilled sourdough bakers with years of experience working with high hydration doughs made with predominantly stoneground flour. 

Our baking team is characterized by its constant questioning, learning, open-minded approach to bread and sourdough. And they are not only skilled bakers, but experienced and passionate teachers.

Oh, and you also get to go home with a whooooole lot of bread. 🥖

Harvest Season! 

Ben has been growing about 20 different varieties of wheat on a diversity plot @fellows_farm made up of a collection of winter and spring wheats. 

‘Winter wheats’ are wheat varieties that are sown in winter and harvested in summer. With the long, slow period of growth this can translate to higher nutritional content (and more flavour). 

‘Spring wheats’ are sown in spring and harvested in summer. This makes for a shorter growing season so, if we have an *ahem* disappointing summer the grain hasn’t had the opportunity to grow and ripen sufficiently, making it overall less well-adapted to an increasingly unpredictable climate than its winter equivalent. 

Some of our e5 crew popped up to @fellowsfarm where we had a lot of fun hand-harvesting with traditional sickels (kindly provided by @brockwell_bake). Mirroring the same movements and using the same tools that people have used for countless generations, we chatted about grain, baking and the future of milling and farming. Now all the wheat has been gathered into sheathes and will rest until mid-autumn. We’re excited to do some initial test-milling and baking to see how the grain varieties behave and to decide which grains to grow next!

Part of the work e5 has been doing over the last decade is to explore how to encourage more diversity in the cereals farmed in the UK and how to grow them sustainably. Although we’ve suffered some losses, we have also had great successes! We hope to harvest about 80 tonnes of heritage, organic wheat to be milled on our stone-mill in Hackney. This flour makes up about 60% of the flour used in your favourites: the Hackney Wild and the Stockholm. 

Some of the varieties of wheat listed below have been grown this year on our diversity plot:

Haruani, Miller’s Choice, Retour Population, Purple Naked Spelt, Czech Red Wheat, Oak Hill Farm Population, Emmer, Oland, Einkorn, Florence Aurora and more!

Sharing seeds is an ancient practice that is founded in generosity and mutual support. Thank you to all those who have shared their seeds with us over the years of whom there are too many to list here.

We’ve teamed up with our friends at E5 to create a National Welsh Rarebit Day special, using La Fromagerie cheese and E5 bread. We’ve been selling E5’s delicious sourdough at our shops for years and are great supporters of their ethos and commitment to sustainability.

The Welsh Rarebit Special will be on the lunch menu at La Fromagerie Marylebone on Sunday 3rd September and E5 Bakehouse on Monday 4th September.
 
If you want to try to make it at home, you can find a recipe below and most of the ingredients stocked in our shops:
 
A Traditional Welsh Rarebit based on 
@alessandro.grano ‘s recipe (Serves 4)
-  Pamplie Unsalted Butter, 50g
-  Plain Flour, 50g
-  Dijon Extra Strong, 1tsp
-  Cayenne Pepper, ½ tsp
-  Valdespino Sherry Vinegar, 2 tsp
-  Kernel Export Porter, 100ml
-  Keen’s Farmhouse Cheddar, 450g
-  Orchard Eggs, 1 Yolk
-  Worcestershire Sauce, 1 Splash
-  E5 Bread
 
1. Make a roux with the butter and flour, you can make it quite nutty brown
2. Add the porter in parts, whisking constantly to prevent lumps
3. When the mixture has started to thicken, add the cheddar, sherry vinegar, mustard, cayenne pepper and Worcestershire sauce
4. Stir until smooth
5. Take off the heat and add egg yolk to enrich (you can use hot or cold from the fridge)
6. Toast or grill the bread on both sides
7. Top with the rarebit mix and grill until golden and bubbling (about 5 mins)
8. Add Worcestershire sauce to the top to taste

We are not wine experts but luckily our wine suppliers are! They have helped us stock our shelves with a carefully curated selection of natural wines used in low-input viniculture systems. Wine terminology is complicated and we’re not about to get involved in a ‘natural’ wine debate but what we do know is that many of the wines we sell have been made in a way that reflects our own values and approach. Wines made using spontaneous fermentation (aka not adding a ‘culture’) is the wine equivalent of sourdough. The yeast and bacteria that ferment the wine aren’t added but are already present in the fruit itself. This means the wine is the truest expression of the fruit and the soil in which it’s grown. Similar to sourdough bread baking, this process has been around for thousands of year and has not been invented recently in a small village in France. They do excellent wines tho 😘 It’s about honouring the processes that people before us went through to get to this incredibly diverse variety.

Bread and wine, wine and bread, it’s what we’re made of. 

Come and taste some of our regular wines and a selection of new ones.

Everyone knows that at e5 we’re all about bread but did you know how much we love butter? We’re so passionate about it we use 3 different types. Most butter available in the shops in the UK is ‘sweet butter’, this means that it is made directly from cream with or without salt to help preserve it. Cultured butter is a fermented product similar to cheese. Lactic bacteria or a ‘culture’ is added (unless it is made from raw milk in which case it is sometimes fermented using the bacteria that is already present within the cream aka the sourdough of the dairy world). This culture works to break down the sugars in the milk which makes it more digestible, nutritious but most importantly, more flavourful! 
We use a raw, cultured butter from @fenfarmdairy for all our laminated doughs aka croissants, pasties, buns, galettes and a cultured @estatedairy butter in our cakes, cookies and drizzled all over our famous scrambled eggs. AND we serve @glastonbury whey butter alongside our sourdough toast. Have you noticed the butteriness of any of our products?

🧈 Butter, it turns out, can vary with the seasons. The cows diet changes depending on the pasture and this in turn affects the milk they produce and therore for  butter that is churned. We try to stay in tune with how the butters are behaving and we’re constantly adapting our methods and recipes to stay responsive and oh boy it keeps us on our toes. 

Historically, many bakeries would value consistency in their butter over any other trait. But here at e5 we value flavour, sustainable farming practices and supporting local producers. If the butter stayed the same all the time it would make our lives easier for sure, but would it be as fun? Probably not… 

🌱 For those of you preferring a plantbased diet we use @naturli and @honest_toil in our vegan cakes and pastries such as the chocolate babka. 

You can find @fenfarmdairy Bungay butter in the cheese fridge in our shop!

Sweet spices. Every year they make a return to a selection of our baked goods and take centre stage. The pastry team fills the air in the bakery with a blend of different aromas - making our special speculaas mix, grating (a lot of)  nutmeg, toasting cardamom seeds, folding through cinnamon in the butter, baking off fresh Stollen, simmering infused syrups and creams… the baristas are busy steaming milk to blend with our chai mix destined for a warming cup on the colder days and the kitchen is making great seasonal chutneys and compotes to adorn our daily mains, sandwiches or those much loved pancakes! 

We haven’t shown enough love or appreciation for them on this platform, yet they’re such an interesting and important aspect of the Bakehouse! Spices are generally grouped into roots, bark, seeds and fruits from plants, and are predominantly used to add flavour to our foods and for a variety of medicinal purposes. It’s fair to say our whole world has been shaped by the spice trade, which is a lengthy story with a lot of violence and an exploitative colonial history. There are also a lot of beautiful and untold heritage stories to still discover that are inherently linked to the people cultivating, growing and drying these spices and how we came to enjoy them in our dishes and at what cost.

Some very talented humans have devoted their time and knowledge into researching the cultural, historical, economical and emotional aspects that are linked with spices and their trade. These academics, home cooks, grassroots collectives, artists and ethical spice companies all play an essential role in challenging a very big industry. We recommend listening to @annasulan podcast Taste of Place.

There is a plethora of information out there on the spice trade and the limitations of characters in an IG post just isn’t sufficient. We’ve come to know there is much still to learn and unlearn. Please feel free to give a shout out to those individuals, businesses and orgs that are trying to make a difference and make sure their voices and efforts are heard in the comments below. ⤵️

This week’s annual staff party was absolutely brilliant! ✨ Central to the night is always a communal meal. Picture this: 85 of us, from both our Poplar and Hackney sites, sat down at long tables adorned with mouthwatering dishes. The food was a celebration of mostly plant based cooking (except for that Ghanaian chicken with shito sauce… ooooffff perfection 🤤) and everyone knows we can’t throw a party without using chickpeas. If you know our daily mains, this incredible and versatile pulse takes centre stage on a regular basis. 

So we decided to make Trinidadian style doubles, barra (the deep fried bread) are topped with spicy channa (chickpeas) and served with a variety of different toppings such as dry coconut chutney, green mango chutney, tamarind sauce, cooling cucumber, hot pepper sauce and some extra green seasoning because why not! We served them alongside scotch bonnet and honey roasted sprouts on romesco sauce and fragrant pilau rice. Not to forget about the dhal puri, rotis and tamarind sauce we got from @horizonfoodsroti in Tottenham (thank you to the kind owner that took me to the train station carrying 120 breads, reminiscing about their Hackney times. Everyone was savouring the flavour packed dishes inspired by recipes from the wonderful books East Winds by @riazphillips and Plentiful by @denaimoore (you can find some copies on our shelves if you feel inspired!). What was your e5 highlight of the year?

As the first days of the new calendar year arrived it came with some reflections on the year’s past… 
It’s been a big year in many ways, and there’s too much we’d like to say that will fit this one post but here goes a meaningful summary of 2023 at e5 Bakehouse:

We’re proud to say our loaves are now made with 100% stoneground, organic, British grown flour. Much of this flour is sourced by procuring grain directly from farmers around the UK and our own farm @fellows_farm which we then mill on on our stone mills in Hackney and Suffolk, but we also continue to work with several other wonderful flour producers. All those delicious lunches, pastries, cakes, sandwiches, jams, chutneys and fermented goods are still made with almost all organic and/or locally produced ingredients 💛

We started, and assisted with a variety of new, charitable programmes in collaboration with local partners and in doing so made loads of new friends: Daily Bread with @saint.church in Hackney, @curryclubldn at the @hackneychinese and with the @teviotcentre Food Coop in Tower Hamlets. We also held our first (Not) Just Bread Programme again in collaboration with the @refugeecouncil since Covid 19. Currently, we are raising funds for the next one so we can continue this work in spring this year (already had one beautiful dinner by Sarah and Aitana @littlecookingpot keep your eyes peeled!)

A cold morning in London makes us dream of the Alpujarras… 🌅 

For many years we have proudly been organising baking retreats in collaboration with Emma and David at Las Chimeneas. @laschimeneas  It’s located in the dramatic region of the Alpujarras in Spain and the accommodation consists of beautifully converted village houses to welcome all guests. 

Expect lots of antiques, books and hidden nooks and crannies! The landscape is incredibly varied, making it perfect for long walks or just staring at the sunsets and on hot days you’ll be able to enjoy a dip in the pool… During the baking retreat there will be two experienced teachers that’ll be taking you through all the essentials of sourdough bread baking with local grains and e5 flour taken from our mill in Hackney. 

Over the course of the week, there will be two full days of sourdough bread making and new to the course is a half day pastry workshop. We will prepare our shortcrust dough by using a variety of flours, we will go on making a nutty frangipane with locally grown almonds and top it with seasonal or preserved fruit. This elegant frangipane tart will be ready to enjoy over the next few days with a lovely cup of coffee or tea! 🍊
